# {"source": "Australian Press Council adjudication (privacy breach, pregnancy reported before the woman announced it)", "article": "Local entrepreneur Dana Cole is expecting her first child this spring, sources close to the family confirmed, a happy turn for the businesswoman after a difficult year.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Dana Cole is expecting her first child this spring", "span": [19, 69], "issue_label": "private pregnancy reported without consent", "question": "Has Dana Cole announced this herself? If she has not told family, friends, or colleagues yet, we are breaking that news for her, to everyone, at once. What is the public interest that outweighs her right to choose when and whether?", "why_it_matters": "The Australian Press Council upheld a privacy breach over a paper reporting a woman's pregnancy she had not announced, finding the premature reporting would be substantially distressing to anyone in her situation.", "fix_suggestion": "Unless there is a genuine public interest, hold the detail until she announces it herself, or get her explicit consent to report it now.", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Australian Press Council adjudication (privacy breach, domestic violence complainant named and pictured)", "article": "The woman, Sarah Bennett of Maple Street, told the court her former partner had threatened her for months. A photograph of Bennett outside the courthouse accompanies this article.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Sarah Bennett of Maple Street", "span": [11, 40], "issue_label": "domestic violence complainant named and located", "question": "The Australian Press Council upheld a privacy breach on this exact pattern: complainant named, street given, courthouse photograph run. Her former partner now has all three.", "why_it_matters": "We just rebuilt her threat model for the person she sought a restraining order against.", "fix_suggestion": "Withhold her name and street, and do not run an identifying photograph. The story works without putting her in danger.", "replacement": "The woman, who asked not to be identified for her safety,", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Source-protection practice; the combination of details builds a searchable dossier", "article": "Maria Lopez, 34, an undocumented housekeeper who lives in the Sunset Park neighbourhood, said her employer has not paid her for six weeks.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Maria Lopez, 34, an undocumented housekeeper who lives in the Sunset Park neighbourhood", "span": [0, 87], "issue_label": "complete dossier on an undocumented source", "question": "Full name, age, immigration status, occupation, neighbourhood, all in one sentence. ICE has subpoenaed newsrooms on less. Did Maria understand we would narrow her this far?", "why_it_matters": "Each detail is harmless alone; together they are a searchable file with a deportation pathway at the end of it.", "fix_suggestion": "Use a first-name pseudonym, broaden the neighbourhood to the borough, and keep the immigration status only if it is essential and she agreed to it being public.", "replacement": "Maria, a housekeeper in Brooklyn who asked that her full name not be used because of her immigration status,", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Source-protection practice on identifying minors in sensitive stories", "article": "Jordan, 12, a sixth-grader at Oak Ridge Middle School, has been living in a shelter with his mother since they were evicted in March.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Jordan, 12, a sixth-grader at Oak Ridge Middle School", "span": [0, 53], "issue_label": "minor identified in a story about poverty", "question": "A twelve-year-old, first name, age, and exact school. His classmates will see this on Friday. Did his mother understand that naming the school narrows him down to one of about thirty children?", "why_it_matters": "Children identified in stories about poverty, addiction, or homelessness carry the consequences with their peers and into a permanent record they never agreed to. The school name does most of the identifying work here.", "fix_suggestion": "Drop the school name or generalise it, and consider a pseudonym. The story does not need the identifier to land.", "replacement": "Jordan, 12, who has been living in a shelter with his mother since they were evicted in March", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Ethics practice on using trauma as a hook without follow-up infrastructure", "article": "She still flinches at loud noises. In her first interview since the attack, the survivor described the night in detail, her voice breaking as she spoke.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "In her first interview since the attack, the survivor described the night in detail, her voice breaking as she spoke", "span": [35, 151], "issue_label": "trauma used as a hook with no infrastructure", "question": "Dart Center guidance is explicit: do not open on the worst night without consent on the framing and a contact channel afterwards. We opened on her worst night. Did she sign off on which line we used?", "why_it_matters": "Without consent on the framing and a way to reach us afterward, the story extracts from her and gives nothing back.", "fix_suggestion": "Confirm she understood how the account would be used and how prominently, and add a way for her to reach the newsroom after publication.", "replacement": null, "severity": "medium"}]}
# {"source": "Source-protection practice; predictable locations of threatened sources", "article": "Ahmed, who has received threats since arriving in the city last year, spoke to reporters outside the mosque on Elm Street where he attends Friday prayers.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "outside the mosque on Elm Street where he attends Friday prayers", "span": [89, 153], "issue_label": "predictable location of a threatened source", "question": "We have just told the people threatening him exactly where he will be, every Friday, at the same time. Does the exact mosque and street add anything the story actually needs?", "why_it_matters": "Locating a threatened source at a specific, regular gathering place creates a foreseeable harassment pathway. The story is about threats against him; we should not be improving the targeting.", "fix_suggestion": "Generalise the location. 'Spoke to reporters in the city' or 'after Friday prayers' carries the scene without the street.", "replacement": "spoke to reporters after Friday prayers", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Ethics practice on a source losing control of the framing", "article": "Asked about the hardest part, she said quietly, 'Some days I just don't know how I'll make rent.' The quote will run as the article's pull text and social card.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "The quote will run as the article's pull text and social card", "span": [98, 159], "issue_label": "source loses control of the framing", "question": "She consented to the interview, not the pull quote. A line about not making rent becoming her social card is a separate decision, and we made it, not her.", "why_it_matters": "The line she will be known for on the internet is now the most exposing line in the piece, chosen without her.", "fix_suggestion": "Pick a pull quote that does not reduce her to her hardest moment, or check with her on which line she is comfortable being known by.", "replacement": null, "severity": "medium"}]}
# {"source": "Dart Center guidance on interviewing trauma survivors", "article": "The reporter pressed the grieving mother on the details of the crash within minutes of arriving, telling her, 'I understand what you're going through.'", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "telling her, 'I understand what you're going through.'", "span": [97, 151], "issue_label": "retraumatising interview approach", "question": "Did the reporter actually say 'I understand what you're going through' to a mother who just lost a child, and open with the hardest details? If the piece is presenting this as normal practice, it should not be.", "why_it_matters": "The Dart Center's guidance is explicit: never say 'I understand' or 'I know how you feel', and do not lead with the hardest questions. Both can retraumatise a source, and both are avoidable.", "fix_suggestion": "If this is the reporter's own conduct, it is a process problem to fix before the next interview. If it is a detail in the story, cut it unless the interviewing approach is itself the subject.", "replacement": null, "severity": "medium"}]}
{"source": "Ethics practice on identity details that are not load-bearing", "article": "The suspect, an immigrant from Eastern Europe who speaks limited English, was arrested on Tuesday.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "an immigrant from Eastern Europe who speaks limited English", "span": [13, 72], "issue_label": "identity detail that is not load-bearing", "question": "Does Eastern Europe or limited English have anything to do with the alleged crime? If not, the AP Stylebook calls this exactly the line that invites the reader to do the stereotyping for us.", "why_it_matters": "When origin or language are not load-bearing, repeating them is the writer's choice to link the trait to the conduct.", "fix_suggestion": "Cut the origin and language detail unless it is directly relevant. If it is, make the relevance explicit.", "replacement": "The suspect was arrested on Tuesday", "severity": "medium"}]}
{"source": "WHO and Samaritans media guidelines on reporting suicide", "article": "Mark Davies, a 24-year-old graphic designer, died by suicide on Tuesday at his apartment on Wilson Avenue. He hanged himself with a tie, police said. Friends said he had been struggling with depression.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "He hanged himself with a tie, police said", "span": [107, 148], "issue_label": "method of suicide described in detail", "question": "WHO and Samaritans suicide-reporting guidelines are explicit: detailed method increases imitation, particularly in younger readers. We have published method and location. Does the public interest in either outweigh the documented copycat risk?", "why_it_matters": "Detailed suicide method in print is the line research has tied directly to copycat behaviour.", "fix_suggestion": "Strike the method and the location. Lead with his life, end with the 988 line.", "replacement": "Mark Davies, 24, died by suicide on Tuesday. Friends said he had been struggling with depression. (Resources: if you are in distress, call or text 988.)", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Ethics practice on naming sexual assault survivors", "article": "Jenna Walker, 19, has come forward to accuse her former boss of sexual assault. Walker, who works at a coffee shop in the Riverside neighbourhood, said the assault occurred in October.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Jenna Walker, 19", "span": [0, 16], "issue_label": "sexual assault survivor named without strong consent process", "question": "Walker is a 19-year-old accuser who has not been through a trial. Did she consent to being named with full understanding that her name will be searchable on her future jobs and dates for the rest of her life? Did a counsellor walk through that with her?", "why_it_matters": "Most newsrooms do not name sexual assault accusers without their explicit, informed consent. The long tail is the issue: she may consent at 19 and regret it permanently. The standard is to ask twice, in writing.", "fix_suggestion": "Withhold the last name unless she has given informed, written consent. If she insists on full identification, add a paragraph noting her stated reason so readers see this was her decision.", "replacement": "Jenna, 19, who agreed to be identified by her first name only,", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Ethics practice on identifying juvenile suspects", "article": "Two boys, aged 14 and 15, were charged Tuesday with the burglary at the Ridgemont Mall. They are Tyler Mason, of Westgate Drive, and Daniel Kim of Maple Court.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "They are Tyler Mason, of Westgate Drive, and Daniel Kim of Maple Court", "span": [88, 158], "issue_label": "juveniles named in a charge", "question": "Both boys are minors. Juvenile records are sealed because we recognise the disproportion between a 14-year-old and a name that will follow him to every future job. What public interest names them on a mall burglary?", "why_it_matters": "Naming them forecloses the rehabilitation the sealed-record system exists to allow.", "fix_suggestion": "Withhold names and streets. Report the charges, the ages, and the school district at most.", "replacement": "Two boys, aged 14 and 15, were charged Tuesday with the burglary at the Ridgemont Mall", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Ethics practice on door-stepping bereaved families", "article": "A reporter reached the family's front porch within an hour of the police notification and asked Mrs Calloway how she was feeling about her son's death.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "asked Mrs Calloway how she was feeling about her son's death", "span": [90, 150], "issue_label": "door-stepping a family minutes after notification", "question": "Did we approach this family within an hour of the notification, and is the first question we asked really 'how are you feeling'? The Dart Center, the SPJ code, and most editors' guidance specifically warn against this. Why is the piece presenting this as routine?", "why_it_matters": "Approaching bereaved families immediately after notification, especially through unannounced contact, is identified across the journalism-ethics literature as a form of harm we routinely cause sources. It is also the kind of detail that makes readers turn against the outlet permanently.", "fix_suggestion": "Hold contact until the family signals they are ready, or work through a family-liaison or an officer. If we approach, do it with their consent and let them set the time.", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Privacy practice on revealing medical history without consent", "article": "Officer Whitman, who has been on disability leave since 2021 for treatment of bipolar disorder, was named today as the off-duty officer who returned fire at the gas station.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "who has been on disability leave since 2021 for treatment of bipolar disorder", "span": [17, 94], "issue_label": "medical condition disclosed unnecessarily", "question": "Is Whitman's diagnosis load-bearing for the story about the gas-station incident? If we cannot show a direct link between his condition and his conduct, we are publishing a stigmatising medical detail for context the reader does not need.", "why_it_matters": "Public-interest tests in privacy practice require a clear connection between the medical detail and the conduct being reported. Otherwise the detail does nothing but stigmatise, with consequences that follow the subject through every future job and relationship.", "fix_suggestion": "Drop the medical detail unless we can show, with on-the-record sourcing, that it is directly relevant to the conduct. If it is, say so plainly with that sourcing.", "replacement": "Officer Whitman, who has been on disability leave since 2021,", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Privacy practice on outing", "article": "Senator Hayes, who is gay, voted against the marriage equality bill on Tuesday.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Senator Hayes, who is gay", "span": [0, 25], "issue_label": "outing without confirmation of public status", "question": "Is the senator out publicly, or are we breaking that for him? Even if multiple people have told us, a person's sexuality is theirs to disclose. The vote can be reported without it.", "why_it_matters": "Outing a person, even a public figure, is a serious privacy intrusion in most press codes. There is a recognised public-interest test (hypocrisy, public conduct that contradicts a stated position) but it requires clear evidence and a high bar.", "fix_suggestion": "Confirm whether Hayes has publicly identified as gay. If he has, the line can stand if it is relevant. If he has not, hold it unless the hypocrisy bar is clearly cleared and we can document it.", "replacement": "Senator Hayes voted against the marriage equality bill on Tuesday", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Privacy practice on identifying jurors", "article": "Juror number 7, identified by sources as Ms Patel, a 42-year-old nurse from the Eastlake neighbourhood, was the holdout that produced the hung jury.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Juror number 7, identified by sources as Ms Patel, a 42-year-old nurse from the Eastlake neighbourhood", "span": [0, 102], "issue_label": "juror identified outside the courtroom", "question": "Was Ms Patel's name released by the court, or are we naming her against the empanelment? Identifying a juror who has not chosen to be public exposes her to harassment, retaliation, and intimidation, and undermines the next jury in the next high-profile case.", "why_it_matters": "Identifying jurors against their wishes is an ethics red flag across most codes and a contempt risk in many jurisdictions. Future jurors learn from what happens to past ones; the chilling effect on willingness to serve is documented.", "fix_suggestion": "Withhold the name, neighbourhood, and identifying details. Report the holdout vote count without naming who voted which way.", "replacement": "One juror was the holdout that produced the hung jury, according to sources familiar with the deliberations", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Source-protection practice on inconsistent pseudonyms", "article": "Aisha, who asked that her real name not be used, said she had been hiding from her ex-husband for two years. Aisha said the police had been slow to respond. 'I work at the Greenstone Salon on Mercer Street,' Aisha said. 'He knows where I work.'", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "I work at the Greenstone Salon on Mercer Street", "span": [158, 205], "issue_label": "pseudonym contradicted by an identifying detail", "question": "We gave Aisha a pseudonym to hide her from her ex-husband, then quoted her naming her workplace and the street. The pseudonym is undone by the quote we left in. Was this checked with her before publication?", "why_it_matters": "An inconsistent pseudonym is worse than no pseudonym: it gives her a false sense of protection while still pointing him at her.", "fix_suggestion": "Generalise the workplace and street, or, with her consent, drop the pseudonym and explain it. Do not leave the half-protection.", "replacement": "I work at a salon in the city. He knows where I work.", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Ethics practice on photographing children at protests and rallies", "article": "Above the article: a photograph of an 8-year-old child holding a sign and shouting at counter-protesters at Saturday's rally.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Above the article: a photograph of an 8-year-old child holding a sign and shouting at counter-protesters at Saturday's rally.", "span": [0, 125], "issue_label": "child identifiable in a polarised public event", "question": "An 8-year-old, identifiable face, at a polarised political rally. That image will follow them through school admissions, future job interviews, and the rest of their life. Did the parents consent to that, knowing how the image travels?", "why_it_matters": "Children's images at political events persist indefinitely; the child's adult privacy outweighs the news value of one dramatic frame.", "fix_suggestion": "Crop or blur the face, choose a wide-shot frame, or use a different image. If the parents have given informed consent for full identification, document it.", "replacement": null, "severity": "medium"}]}
# {"source": "Privacy practice on naming trafficking survivors", "article": "Anna, 22, originally from Bucharest, was rescued from the brothel on Maple Avenue last March. She is working at a restaurant in the Hillside district while she pursues her case in court.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Anna, 22, originally from Bucharest", "span": [0, 35], "issue_label": "trafficking survivor narrowed by origin and location", "question": "Even with the first name only, 'Anna, 22, originally from Bucharest, rescued from a brothel on Maple Avenue, working at a restaurant in Hillside' narrows her to a single person for anyone who wants to find her. Her trafficker, his network, and the family she may have been kept from may all be looking.", "why_it_matters": "Trafficking survivors are among the most vulnerable sources we work with. The combination of origin, age, location of the rescue, and current workplace is a complete identification, despite the pseudonym.", "fix_suggestion": "Strip the origin city, the street of the brothel, and the current neighbourhood. A first-name-only profile with broader geography preserves the story without rebuilding the trafficker's map.", "replacement": "Anna, 22, who was rescued from a brothel in the city last March and is now working in the restaurant industry while she pursues her case in court", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Ethics practice on deception in newsgathering", "article": "Our reporter posed as a potential investor and recorded the meeting without disclosing her affiliation.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "Our reporter posed as a potential investor and recorded the meeting without disclosing her affiliation", "span": [0, 102], "issue_label": "undisclosed deception in newsgathering", "question": "Posing as someone else and secretly recording is the line Editors' Code Clause 10 (SPJ and BBC Editorial Guidelines say the same thing) puts a specific public-interest test on. Was that test applied? Did the editor sign off?", "why_it_matters": "Misrepresentation and secret recording without documented justification is the move that has cost reporters and outlets badly when challenged in court.", "fix_suggestion": "Document the public-interest justification, alternatives considered, and editor sign-off. If those were not in place, do not publish the recorded material.", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Ethics practice on a source who later asks to be removed", "article": "After publication, the source emailed asking that her name be removed from the article. The newsroom did not respond.", "critiques": [{"agent": "human_rights", "text_quote": "The newsroom did not respond.", "span": [88, 117], "issue_label": "post-publication reconsideration ignored", "question": "She agreed at the time, then asked to be removed. The newsroom did not respond. Did anything change for her safety, her employment, her family? A source's post-publication request is not always honoured, but it is always answered.", "why_it_matters": "Press codes increasingly recognise a duty to respond to post-publication concerns, especially from vulnerable sources. Silence is the worst possible reply because it tells the source we never cared.", "fix_suggestion": "Respond. Explain the public-interest test that keeps her name in the piece, or remove it if the test does not hold. Either way, the answer is a conversation.", "replacement": null, "severity": "medium"}]}
{"source": "Example of a public figure speaking within their public role", "article": "The police commissioner, speaking at a news conference, said the department would review its use-of-force policy after the incident.", "critiques": []}
# {"source": "Example of a source who has consented to being named, with no retaliation pathway", "article": "Rosa Patel, a tenants' union organiser who agreed to be named, said the eviction moratorium's expiry would put hundreds of families at risk.", "critiques": []}
# {"source": "Example of standard reporting detail that does not single out a vulnerable source", "article": "The crash happened just after 8 a.m. on the Route 9 bridge, closing both lanes for three hours, the highway patrol said.", "critiques": []}
{"source": "Example of careful identification of a survivor with full documented consent", "article": "Maria, who agreed to be identified by her first name only after a counsellor walked her through the long-term implications, said the assault changed how she moved through public spaces.", "critiques": []}
